As far as I can see, nobody has ever done this before, perhaps because it is a

00:11:47.002 --> 00:11:53.032
little tenuous, the connections are a little unusual, but I think there are a few

00:11:53.032 --> 00:11:58.712
things that we can learn from The Art of War and apply to our approach to learning

00:11:58.712 --> 00:12:04.032
languages, and that you can apply to your own attitude towards learning English.

00:12:04.792 --> 00:12:06.602
So, let’s give this a go.

00:12:07.932 --> 00:12:11.422
Firstly, here’s a direct quote from The Art of War:

00:12:12.792 --> 00:12:16.992
“Do not repeat the tactics which have gained you one victory, but let

00:12:17.012 --> 00:12:21.552
your methods be regulated by the infinite variety of circumstances.”

00:12:23.022 --> 00:12:27.572
When it comes to fighting a battle, the point here might be obvious - you

00:12:27.572 --> 00:12:32.022
shouldn’t just do the same thing over and over, because the enemy will realise

00:12:32.052 --> 00:12:36.422
what you are doing, and you should be prepared to adapt to different situations.

00:12:37.532 --> 00:12:41.742
Now, can we take anything from this and apply it to learning English?

00:12:42.422 --> 00:12:43.992
I think perhaps we can...

00:12:44.932 --> 00:12:49.542
When many people learn a language, they just do one or two things,

00:12:49.582 --> 00:12:53.852
and assume that because they have got to a certain level with these

00:12:53.992 --> 00:12:58.012
one or two things, they will continue to improve at the same level.

00:12:59.457 --> 00:13:00.297
But that is rarely true.

00:13:01.067 --> 00:13:06.937
What might have worked to get you to a certain point, developing a certain skill, probably won’t

00:13:06.937 --> 00:13:14.146
get you to the next level, it probably won't help you get to where you want to get to next.

00:13:14.146 --> 00:13:18.737
And having a variety of different tools you can use, or tactics,

00:13:18.787 --> 00:13:22.487
as Sun Tzu would say, will mean that you are much better prepared.

00:13:23.537 --> 00:13:30.307
So instead of just being a master of Duolingo or bingeing TV shows on Netflix,

00:13:30.507 --> 00:13:35.777
make sure you write in English, you listen to English podcasts like this one, that

00:13:35.777 --> 00:13:41.207
you do things like Shadowing, and expose yourself to different styles of English.

00:13:42.177 --> 00:13:42.837
Make sense?

00:13:43.257 --> 00:13:43.947
I think it does.

00:13:45.217 --> 00:13:50.507
Our second English learning lesson from The Art of War is, and again this is

00:13:50.507 --> 00:13:55.747
a direct quote, “Strategy without tactics is the slowest route to victory.

00:13:56.427 --> 00:14:00.057
Tactics without strategy are the noise before defeat.”

00:14:01.137 --> 00:14:05.117
The military lesson here is that if you have a plan, but no

00:14:05.187 --> 00:14:09.647
tactics to execute it, you might win but it’ll take a long time.

00:14:10.437 --> 00:14:15.077
If you just have some tactics but no plan, then you will lose.

00:14:15.907 --> 00:14:21.187
Instead, you need both - a plan of action and tactics about how to achieve it.

00:14:22.467 --> 00:14:27.797
If we think about how this might apply to learning anything, including learning

00:14:27.807 --> 00:14:33.357
English, it’s that you’ll have the best results with tactics, so we can interpret

00:14:33.447 --> 00:14:38.727
tactics here are as different tools to improve your English, but you will also

00:14:38.757 --> 00:14:43.667
benefit from an overall plan, a strategy of how to approach your learning.

00:14:44.567 --> 00:14:50.977
You might think that you can just sit down with Netflix, Duolingo, or podcasts and improvements

00:14:51.277 --> 00:14:58.017
will magically come, but they will come faster and more easily with a detailed plan of

00:14:58.207 --> 00:15:03.087
how all of the different tools and approaches you are planning to use will fit together.

00:15:04.287 --> 00:15:09.687
And our final lesson from Sun Tzu’s The Art of War that we can apply to learning English

00:15:09.707 --> 00:15:15.667
is, and again, here’s a direct quote: “Opportunities multiply as they are seized."

00:15:16.907 --> 00:15:22.707
When we think about this referring to warfare it means: when you see an opportunity,

00:15:23.137 --> 00:15:28.017
take it if it is sensible as it will probably lead to more opportunities.

00:15:29.257 --> 00:15:34.597
Now, how is he going to claim this relates to learning English, you might be asking yourself?

00:15:35.077 --> 00:15:40.284
Well, I think we can interpret it in exactly the same way, that if you see

00:15:40.304 --> 00:15:45.904
opportunities to engage in English, to chat to others in English, to join English

00:15:45.934 --> 00:15:52.404
communities, when you find an opportunity to use English, take it because it will

00:15:52.404 --> 00:15:58.204
likely lead to more opportunities, which will themselves lead to more opportunities.

00:15:59.454 --> 00:16:04.044
But there’s one huge difference between learning English and The Art of War,

00:16:04.524 --> 00:16:08.624
and that is that learning a language shouldn’t be thought of as a battle.

00:16:08.984 --> 00:16:13.184
There is no enemy, despite how you might feel about phrasal verbs.

00:16:13.754 --> 00:16:18.904
You aren’t fighting against anyone, and indeed the magical thing about

00:16:18.904 --> 00:16:23.654
learning a language is that it isn’t a competition, so you might be

00:16:23.654 --> 00:16:26.764
thinking that you should ignore all of the advice you’ve just heard.

00:16:28.034 --> 00:16:34.184
But perhaps, just perhaps, there is something that you can take from this 2,500 year

00:16:34.184 --> 00:16:39.944
old book, and if it does help you with your English learning, then you won’t be the

00:16:40.184 --> 00:16:45.184
first, and certainly won’t be the last, to be guided by the works of Master Sun.

